59":"1259","1215":"1215","1325":"1325","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1175":"1175","about 1200":"omkring 1200","1184":"1184","1208":"1208","about 1175":"omkring 1175","1290":"1290","Sheviock, Cornwall, England":"Sheviock, Cornwall, England","Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1175–":"circa 1175–Overleden","1184–Female":"1184–Overleden","1200–Male":"1200–Overleden","1208–1325":"1208–1325","1175–Male":"1175–Overleden","about 1208":"circa 1208","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1325":"1325","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1175":"1175","about 1200":"circa 1200","1184":"1184","1208":"1208","about 1175":"circa 1175","1290":"1290","Sheviock, Cornwall, England":"Sheviock, Cornwall, England","Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, England"},"en":{"about 1175–":"about 1175–Deceased","1184–Female":"1184–Deceased","1200–Male":"1200–Deceased","1208–1325":"1208–1325","1175–Male":"1175–Deceased","about 1208":"about 1208","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1325":"1325","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1175":"1175","about 1200":"about 1200","1184":"1184","1208":"1208","about 1175":"about 1175","1290":"1290","Sheviock, Cornwall, England":"Sheviock, Cornwall, England","Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dawnay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: locative name from one of the many places in northern France named from an alder grove (Old French  <i>aulnai</i>,  <i>aulnoi</i>, latinized as  <i>alnetum</i>), such as Annay (Pas-de-Calais), Aulnay (Aube, Marne, Calvados), Aulnois (Aisne), and Aunay (Calvados, Eure-et-Loire, Seine-et-Oise). With fused preposition, Anglo-Norman French  <i>d'Aunai</i> became  <i>Dawnay</i>,  <i>Dawney</i> and (with loss of the final syllable)  <i>Dawn</i>.   Laney   is another form of this surname with fused definite article.  See also  Dando  , from Anglo-Norman French  <i>d'Aunou</i>, with which  <i>d'Aunai</i> may sometimes have been confused."],"variants":[{"name":"Dawney","meanings":["Norman, English:  See  Dawnay  ."]},{"name":"Laney","meanings":["Irish: probably a shortened and altered form of   McElhinney  .","English and Irish: habitational name introduced by the Normans originally deriving from any of the many places in northern France called L'Aunai (from Latin <i>alnetum</i> ‘alder grove’). It may also have developed to   Delaney  .","Variant of   Laine   2, a surname of French origin."]},{"name":"Dawn","meanings":["English (Derbyshire and Nottinghamshire): of Norman origin, probably a clipped form of <b>Dawnay</b> or <b>Dawney</b> (compare   Dana  ), habitational names from one of the many places in northern France named for an alder grove (Old French <i>aulnai</i>, <i>aulnoi</i>, Latinized as <i>alnetum</i>). With fused preposition <i>d(e)</i>, Anglo-Norman <i>d'Aunai</i> became <i>Dawnay</i>, <i>Dawney</i> and (with loss of the final syllable) <i>Dawn</i>.   Laney   is another form of this surname with fused definite article. See also   Dando  , from Anglo-Norman <i>d'Aunou</i>, with which <i>d'Aunai</i> may sometimes have been confused.","English: from Middle English <i>Dawen</i>, a variant of   Dawes   with the weak declension genitival suffix <i>-(e)n</i> (Old English <i>-an</i>) instead of the standard Middle English <i>-es</i>. The usage is mainly restricted to West Midlands dialects of Middle English.","Americanized form of German   Daun  ."]},{"name":"Doney","meanings":["English (Cornwall): of uncertain origin. There is a Richard <i>Donowe</i> recorded in 1451-64 as a tenant in Manuels, Saint Columb Minor, whose surname appears to be a pet form of an unidentified personal name with the Cornish hypocoristic suffix <i>-ow</i>. Formally this might have become <i>Doney</i> but <i>Donowe</i> itself seems not to have survived, unless it was altered to   Downey  . However, there is no evidence to suggest any connection of this west Cornwall surname with <i>Doney</i> in central and east Cornwall (Bodmin and Quethiock). Alternatively, perhaps it is a variant of the Devon name   Downey  , and with the main vowel shortened and lowered, but evidence for this is lacking.","Americanized form of French Canadian   Daunais   or   Donais  ."]},{"name":"Dando","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name for someone from Aunou-le-Faucon in Orne, Normandy, with fused preposition. Aunou was named for an alder grove, from Latin <i>alnus</i> ‘alder’ + the Gaulish suffix <i>-avum</i>. In medieval England <i>d'Aunou</i> developed an intrusive <i>-d-</i>, giving <i>Dando</i>. The surname was sometimes confused with <i>d'Aunay</i> or <i>d'Auney</i> (see   Delaney  )."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":40,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":49,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":84,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":115,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sir William Dawnay was born about 1175, in Sheviock, Cornwall, England. He had at least 2 sons with Idonea de Beauchamp."},"et":{"about 1175–":"umbes 1175–Surnud","1184–Female":"1184–Surnud","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1208–1325":"1208–1325","1175–Male":"1175–Surnud","about 1208":"umbes 1208","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1325":"1325","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1175":"1175","about 1200":"umbes 1200","1184":"1184","1208":"1208","about 1175":"umbes 1175","1290":"1290","Sheviock, Cornwall, England":"Sheviock, Cornwall, England","Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1175–":"noin 1175–Kuollut","1184–Female":"1184–Kuollut","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1208–1325":"1208–1325","1175–Male":"1175–Kuollut","about 1208":"noin 1208","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1325":"1325","1224":"1224","1200":"1200","1175":"1175","about 1200":"noin 1200","1184":"1184","1208":"1208","about 1175":"noin 1175","1290":"1290","Sheviock, Cornwall, England":"Sheviock, Cornwa